Australian Frontier Wars: Waterloo Creek Massacre (26 Jan 1838) Result: Colonial victory, Aboriginals driven from Gwydir River territory. Was a battle at Waterloo Creek between Kamilaroi Aboriginals and Sydney mounted police. Sydney mounted police (2 sergeants, 20 troopers) led by Major James Nunn pursued the Kamilaroi to upper Gwydir River, following the murder of 5 British stockmen in recently established pastoral runs on the upper Gwydir River area of New South Wales. On the morning of Jan 26, there was a surprise attack on Nunn's party, leaving Corporal Hannan wounded with a spear in his leg and 5 dead Aboriginals. The Aboriginals fled down river and the remaining British pursued them, led by Lieutenant George Cobban. Cobban's party found their quarry about a mile down the river at a point now known as Waterloo Creek, where a second engagement took place. The encounter lasted several hours and no Aboriginals were captured. Modern estimates put at 300 dead Aboriginals with no British casualties.

History of the Codex Amiatinus: Originally three copies of the Bible were commissioned by Abbot Ceolfrid in 692. This date has been established as the double monastery of Monkwearmouthâ€“Jarrow secured a grant of additional land to raise the 2,000 head of cattle needed to produce the vellum. Bede was most likely involved in the compilation. In 716, Ceolfrid accompanied one copy, the Codex Amiatinus, intended as a gift to Pope Gregory II, but he died en route to Rome on 29 September 716 at Langres, Burgundy. The book later appears in the 9th century in Abbey of the Saviour, Mount Amiata in Tuscany (hence the description "Amiatinus"), where it is recorded in a list of the Abbey's relics dated 1036, describing it as being an Old and New Testament 'written in the hand of the blessed Pope Gregory'. It remained in the San Salvatore Monastery until 1786 when it passed to the Laurentian Library in Florence. The dedication page had been altered and the principal librarian to the Laurentian, Angelo Maria Bandini suggested that the author was Servandus, a follower of St. Benedict, and that it had been produced at Monte Cassino around the 540s. This claim was accepted for the next hundred years, establishing it as the oldest copy of the Vulgate, but scholars in Germany noted the similarity to 9th-century texts. In 1888, Giovanni Battista de Rossi established that the Codex was related to the Bibles mentioned by Bede. This also established that Amiatinus was related to the Greenleaf Bible fragment in the British Library. Although de Rossi's attribution removed 150 years from the age of the Codex, it remains the oldest version of the Vulgate and the oldest complete Christian bible in any language. As the primary source of the Vulgate, the manuscript was of particular importance to the Catholics during the Counter-Reformation. Protestant translations derived from the original language of the Scriptures, but the Latin text of the Amiatinus was earlier than any then-known Hebrew manuscript, making it a "major piece of propaganda in the battle for textual precedence". In 1587 Pope Sixtus V demanded the book be sent to Rome where it was consulted for a new papal edition of the Bible, the Sixtine Vulgate; although in the event, little or no use was made of its readings in either the Sistine or subsequent Sixto-Clementine official Vulgate editions, whose editors rather preferred later medieval Vulgate texts and editions now known to have been heavily corrupted by non-Vulgate readings. In view of the many accumulated corruptions in all published editions of the Vulgate so far, the Oxford University Press accepted in 1878 a proposal from classicist John Wordsworth (later Bishop of Salisbury) to produce a new critical edition of the Vulgate New Testament. This was eventually published as Nouum Testamentum Domini nostri Iesu Christi Latine, secundum editionem sancti Hieronymi in three volumes between 1889 and 1954; the Codex Amiatinus being a primary source for the entire text; which also followed this manuscript in presenting the text in sense lines, cola et commata without any other indication of punctuation. In 1907 Pope Pius X commissioned the Benedictine monks in Rome to prepare a critical edition of Jerome's Vulgate, entitled Biblia Sacra iuxta latinam vulgatam versionem, which eventually emerged as a counterpart Old Testament to the Oxford New Testament, following largely the same critical principles, and according similar primary status to the Codex Amiatinus text (other than for the Psalms); and similarly deriving its layout, cola et commata from Amiatinus.

The Latin Inflection (Suffix) System. For Nouns and Adjectives, these are grouped into declensions (6): - 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 3rd(i), 4th, 5th. Which are divided by genders (3): - Masculine, Feminine, Neuter. Which are subdivided by numbers (2): - Singular, Plural. Which are subdivided by cases (7). - Nominative, Genitive, Dative, Accusative, Ablative, Vocative, Locative. For Verbs, these are grouped into conjugations (5): - 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 3rd(i), 4th. Which are divided by principals (6): - Indicative, Subjunctive, Infinitive, Particle, Imperative, Gerund. Gerund is subdivided by cases (4): - Genitive, Dative, Accusative, Ablative. The rest are subdivided by forms (2): - Active, Passive. Imperative is subdivided by numbers (2): - Singular, Plural. The rest are subdivided by tenses (6): - Present, Imperfect, Future, Perfect, Pluperfect, Future Perfect. Indicative and Subjunctive are subdivided by numbers (6): - 1st Singular, 2nd Singular, 3rd Singular, 1st Plural, 2nd Plural, 3rd Plural. For Pronouns, these are grouped into ? (7): - 1st Person, 2nd Person, Ille, Iste, Is, Hic, Qui. Which are divided by numbers (2): - Singular, Plural. All but 1st/ 2nd Person are subdivided into genders (3): - Masculine, Feminine, Neuter. Then all are subdivided by cases (7). - Nominative, Genitive, Dative, Accusative, Ablative, Vocative, Locative.

á¶œá´¸ Hablar Fisno: One of the key traits of French is the loss of s, but this trait does exist in one other Romance language, albeit only in particular dialects. That is, in Spanish. The Castilian language, as spoken in Andalucia (southern Spain), the Canary Islands, and the former Spanish Caribbean (mainly Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic) has lost /s/ in most positions but usually finally, either becoming /h/ or entirely silent. Thus, just like French, in these dialects pluralization can only be indicated by the article and conjugation of verbs. Compare los hombres aman las mujeres /loh om.bre a.man lah mu.hÎµr.e/ (the men love the women) with el hombre ama la mujere /Îµl om.bre a.ma la mu.hÎµr/ (the man loves the woman). This has also created a situation of hypercorrection, where speakers of these dialects incorrectly insert /s/ into places where they shouldn't be due to not having a native understanding of where this phoneme should be in the standard dialect - thus words such as fino (fine) become fisno, leading to this practice being given the ironic name of hablar fisno - to attempt to talk in a fancy way, but incorrectly. These dialects also have some other very Francophone traits through pure coincidence, such as ch /tÊƒ/ being pronounced as /Êƒ/, nasalisation of vowels preceding /n/. and final /Îµr/ being articulated as simply /e/.

Description of the Codex Amiatinus: The symbol for it is written am or A (Wordsworth). It is preserved in an immense tome, measuring 19+1â„4 inches (49 cm) high, 13+3â„8 inches (34 cm) in breadth, and 7 inches (18 cm) thick, and weighs over 75 pounds (34 kg) â€“ so impressive, as Hort says, as to fill the beholder with a feeling akin to awe. The Book of Psalms is provided in Jerome's third version, translated from the Hebrew, rather than in the pre-Jerome Roman Psalter then standard in English bibles, or in Jerome's second, Gallican version, that was to supplant his Hebraic Psalms in most Vulgate bibles from the 9th century onwards. By contrast with case in most of the rest of the Old Testament, the Amiatinus psalms text is commonly considered an Â¹inferior witness of Jerome's Versio juxta Hebraicum; the presence of the 'Columba' series of psalm headings, also found in the Cathach of St. Columba, demonstrates that an Irish psalter must have been its source; but the text differs in many places from the best Irish manuscripts. The New Testament is preceded by the Epistula Hieronymi ad Damasum, Prolegomena to the four Gospels. The Codex Amiatinus qualifies as an illuminated manuscript as it has some decoration including two full-page miniatures, but these show little sign of the usual insular style of Northumbrian art and are clearly copied from Late Antique originals. It contains 1,040 leaves of strong, smooth vellum, fresh-looking today despite their great antiquity, arranged in quires of four sheets, or quaternions. It is written in uncial characters, large, clear, regular, and beautiful, two columns to a page, and 43 or 44 lines to a column. A little space is often left between words, but the writing is in general continuous. The text is divided into sections, which in the Gospels correspond closely to the Ammonian Sections. There are no marks of punctuation, but the skilled reader was guided into the sense by stichometric, or verse-like, arrangement into cola and commata, which correspond roughly to the principal and dependent clauses of a sentence. From this manner of writing the script is believed to have been modeled upon the Codex Grandior of Cassiodorus, but it may go back, perhaps, even to St. Jerome. Â¹ "Inferior Psalms": An unsubstantiated opinion of modern Latin Vulgate scholars when comparing to later corrupted Medieval manuscripts.

This is an interesting example of the power of the Latin ablative case, which despite most strongly resembling the modern Romance nouns, actually had a very unique use as stating the means or where/when (either time or space) that something occurred. Here, in the context of St. Paul's trial, he describes how through the means or because of the Jews (judaei - nominative plural, judaeis - ablative plural) which were contradicting his pleas of innocence, here a Latin present participle (no longer existing in Romace languages, replaced with the gerund) is used as a declined adjective - he is forced (passive construct) to appeal to (the) CÃ¦sar. The ablative case is one of the biggest differences between Classical and Late/Medieval Latin as in Classical Latin you could just have a noun declined in the ablative case to indicate the entire idea of it being the means or time/place of something. But in Late Latin and thus the Romance langauges, a proposition such as pro or per became required (which in most Romance languages merged into por). This is mainly due to phonological reasons, as by this point, the ablative case was pronounced the same as the accusative form. á¶œá´¸ -With Pre/Suffix In Iberian Romance Languages: One of the most interesting and archaic aspects of the Iberian Romance languages is the suffix -go, such as in contigo (with you), co(n)migo (with me) and an alternate form in conosco (with us, specifically only in Portuguese). This suffix derived from the Latin suffix -cum, which as a standalone word simply meant with. However, it was suffixed to a pronoun such as nobis (dative form of nos, we) rather than preceding the previous word like 'cum' was usually used, to avoid the situation of 'cum nobis', which according to the great Roman author Cicero, sounded the same as 'cunno bis' - twice in the cunt. Thus all instances of a pronoun and 'cum' followed this example. So 'mecum' - with me, became migo (mecum, mecu, micu, mico, migo) in the Iberian Romance lects. But soon, it was forgotten that the -go suffix in these terms meant the same as 'cum', which had become 'con/com' in the Iberian Romance languages. Thus it was readded to these terms, migo became comigo, tigo because contigo etc. Thus the Spanish phrase conmigo, actually means 'with me with'.

Malay Race The concept of a Malay race was originally proposed by the German physician Johann Friedrich Blumenbach (1752â€“1840), and classified as a brown race. Malay is a loose term used in the late 19th century and early 20th century to describe the Austronesian peoples. The linguistic connections between Madagascar, Polynesia and Southeast Asia were recognized early in the colonial era by European authors, particularly the remarkable similarities between Malagasy, Malay, and Polynesian numerals. The first formal publications on these relationships was in 1708 by the Dutch Orientalist Adriaan Reland, who recognized a "common language" from Madagascar to western Polynesia; although the Dutch explorer Cornelis de Houtman also realized the linguistic links between Madagascar and the Malay Archipelago prior to Reland in 1603. In his 1775 doctoral dissertation titled De Generis Humani Varietate Nativa (trans: On the Natural Varieties of Mankind), Blumenbach outlined Johann Friedrich Blumenbach main human races by skin color, geography, and skull measurements; namely "Caucasians" (white), "Ethiopians" (black), "Americans" (red), and the "Mongolians" (yellow). Blumenbach added Austronesians as the fifth category to his "varieties" of humans in the second edition of De Generis (1781). He initially grouped them by geography and thus called Austronesians the "people from the southern world." In the third edition published in 1795, he named Austronesians the "Malay race" or the "brown race," after studies done by Joseph Banks who was part of the first voyage of James Cook. ------- Blumenbach's description from The anthropological treatises of Johann Friedrich Blumenbach, translated by Thomas Bendyshe, 1865. á¶œá´¸ French Proverb: Quand le bateau coule, les rats quittent le navire. (Like rats deserting a sinking ship) This proverb actually shows something very interesting about the French language. A literal translation would be "when the boat sinks, the rats leave the vessel". The first interesting point is the use of two different words that both mean ship - bateau and navire. Navire comes from Latin Navigium (through a vulgar intermediary of Navilium), while bateau is actually a borrowing from old English bÄt - the source of modern English boat, along with the suffix -eau derived from the Latin diminutive -ellus. The second interesting point is coule (sinks), third person present singular of couler, derives from Latin colare - meaning to filter. Here we see a very large semantic jump from the sense of filtering something with water, to the sense of sinking in water. Another interesting semantic shift is quittent, third person present plural form of quitter - to leave/quit. It is derived from Latin quietare - to quiet, to calm. This is a far bigger shift in meanings, but still understandable as when you leave somewhere you are thus quiet there. The final thing I would like to point out is the word rat, which is derived from the Germanic language Frankish despite rats not being native to Northern Europe in antiquity and them only first appearing in the 12th century, thus it must have originally referred to another animal but came to refer to rats through a semantic change.

á¶œá´¸ The Construct State in Hamito-Semitic and Celtic Languages: Though the Hamito-Semitic languages (e.g. Arabic, Hebrew, Aramaic, Ge'ez, Berber, Ancient Egyptian etc.) at first glance appear to have no commonalities with the Insular Celtic languages (e.g. Welsh, Irish, Breton, Cornish etc.) - however they in fact share a trait that is purely unique to these two language families, and another that is extremely rare among all the world's languages. This is the Construct State, a way of forming the genitive (showing ownership) by placing the possessor directly after the possessed, without any connective word indicating the relationship. For example, in Arabic 'the man's cup' would be ÙƒØ£Ø³ Ø§Ù„Ø±Ø¬Ù„ (ka's al ragul) or 'cup the man'. Equally, in Welsh this same sentence would be cwpan y dyn or 'cup the man'. In both cases (Semitic and Celtic) only the possessor can take the definite article, while the possesed object cannot. Every other language on earth requires a word to indicate a genitive relationship, sometimes independent or sometimes as a prefix or suffix, while these language families do not. This is not the only grammatical trait that the Hamito-Semitic languages have in common, both language families have a VSO syntax or verb-subject-object order. For example, the sentence 'God created the heavens' is ×‘Ö°Ö¼×¨Öµ××©Ö´×Ö–×™×ª ×‘Ö¸Ö¼×¨Ö¸Ö£× ×Ö±×œÖ¹×”Ö´Ö‘×™× ×ÖµÖ¥×ª ×”Ö·×©Ö¸Ö¼××žÖ·Ö–×™Ö´× in Hebrew or 'in-beginning created God the-heavens'. While in Welsh it would be yn y dechreuad creodd Duw y nefoedd or 'in the beginning created God the heavens'. This is less unique, being shared with Austronesian languages such as Tagalog. But this is still an incredibly bizarre trait for the Insular Celtic languages to share with the Hamito-Semitic languages. á¶œá´¸ There is such beauty in Romanian grammar, which remains the closest to Latin out of any Romance language thanks to its retention of a case system. But this in part due to another significant influence on Romanian grammar - the Balkan Sprachbund or Balkan language area. Despite the diverse origins of the languages of the Balkans, Hellenic, Slavic, Albanian, Turkic and of course Latin, all the languages of the region have coalesced together grammatically. Thus instead of placing the definite article before the noun, Romanian places it after the noun, and actually affixes it to the word itself. Thus 'The Dragon' is 'Dracul', drac from Latin draco (dragon) and -ul from Latin ille (that). Compare Italian 'Il Drago'. Romanians also as an ethnic group are incredibly fascinating, as they're the only people to retain Roman as their ethnic name (RomÃ¢n, from Romanus). This is highly unusual, and could have been caused by the fact they were so heavily isolated from other Romanized populations that they had no need of a particular name to differentiate themselves from other Romance peoples. The older form of the word - rumÃ¢n, also had the meaning of peasant and man in general, showing that the word had become increasingly vague in its meaning before the Romanian national awakening. But this also created a very difficult situation for other Romance peoples, as they couldn't refer to Romanians with their own ethnic name without also confusing them with the historical Romans. Thus most Romance languages arbitrarily changed a vowel in the language's word for Roman to create a new term to refer to Romanians. For example, Spanish speakers used Rumano, modelled on Romano. This problem was also overcome in Romanian itself by reborrowing the word from Latin, as the Ã¢ in RomÃ¢n is pronounced as a schwa. Thus to refer to the historical Romans, Romanians simply pronounce this schwa as a true A - Roman. Though Romania is most certainly a Neolatin nation, the Slavic influence on the language, people and faith is undeniable. And this is to their credit in my belief. Definitions of Latin Cases: Nominative: The case used to indicate the subjectâ€”or agentâ€”of a finite verb. Genitive: A noun case used to express some relationship such as possession or origin. It corresponds roughly to the English preposition â€œofâ€ and the suffix â€œ-'sâ€. Dative: The case used to express direction towards an indirect object, the recipient or beneficiary of an action, and is generally indicated in English by to (when a recipient) or for (when a beneficiary) with the objective case. The direct object may be either stated or unstated where the indirect object is the beneficiary of the verbal action, but is stated where the indirect object is a recipient. If there is emphasis on the indirect object, the indirect object usually precedes the direct object and is not usually indicated with to or for; said structure is also used when neither object is being emphasized. Accusative: The case used to mark the immediate object (direct object) on which the transitive verb acts. In Latin grammar, the accusative case (cÄsus accÅ«sÄtÄ«vus) includes functions derived from the Indo-European accusative and lative cases; said Lative Case express concepts similar to those of the English prepositions "to" and "towards". Ablative: A noun case used to indicate movement away from something, removal, separation. In English grammar, it corresponds roughly to the use in English of prepositions "of", "from", "away from", and "concerning". In Latin grammar, the ablative case (cÄsus ablÄtÄ«vus) includes functions derived from the Indo-European ablative, instrumental, comitative, associative and locative cases; these cases express concepts similar to those of the English prepositions "of"/"from", "by", "with", "to"/"with", and "at"/"in", respectively. Here/hence/hither, there/thence/thither, and where/whence/whither are the only English words with separate forms for the ablative (motion away from) and lative (motion towards) cases. Vocative: The case of address, case used for a noun identifying the person or thing being addressed. It corresponds to the archaic English particle "O" as used in solemn or poetic address e.g.: Hear me, O Albion! Locative: The case which indicates a location. It corresponds vaguely to the English prepositions "in", "on", "at", and "by". The locative case belongs to the general local cases, together with the lative and separative case.

This word, which presumably grew out of some sort of Medieval Latin vostra merces/ vostram mercedem, originally meant something along the lines of "your grace" as the most polite form of you, even though merces/ mercy in classical latin meant value. But this formulation would be used in all of the Iberian Romance languages, but radically change based on the language's specific phonological evolution. In Portuguese, vostra(m) mercede(m) evolved into vosmecÃª, due to the loss of the 'str' consonant cluster in Portuguese, compare vosso (yours, plural) with its etymyon vostrum. And the loss of the intervocalic d rendered mercedem as mercÃª. This form has even replaced the traditional tu as the main word for you in many places of Brazil. But in Spanish, a very different path was followed. Vostra(m) mercede(m) instead became vuestra merced, due to the very unique Spanish trait of o diphthongizing into ue. And the retention of the intervocalic d, albeit now no longer intervocalic. This phrase was extremely simplified to (v)ues(tra-merc)ed and finally into the modern Spanish form of usted, which replaced the usual vos in most of the Hispanic world. And this formulation also appears in the Catalan language, which despite not being strictly Iberian but rather Gallo-Romance, has been heavily influenced by Iberian Romance languages. Thus vostÃ© from vostra mercÃ¨ is used, but it retains its meaning as the most polite form of address.

History of the Codex Amiatinus: Originally three copies of the Bible were commissioned by Abbot Ceolfrid in 692. This date has been established as the double monastery of Monkwearmouthâ€“Jarrow secured a grant of additional land to raise the 2,000 head of cattle needed to produce the vellum. Bede was most likely involved in the compilation. In 716, Ceolfrid accompanied one copy, the Codex Amiatinus, intended as a gift to Pope Gregory II, but he died en route to Rome on 29 September 716 at Langres, Burgundy. The book later appears in the 9th century in Abbey of the Saviour, Mount Amiata in Tuscany (hence the description "Amiatinus"), where it is recorded in a list of the Abbey's relics dated 1036, describing it as being an Old and New Testament 'written in the hand of the blessed Pope Gregory'. It remained in the San Salvatore Monastery until 1786 when it passed to the Laurentian Library in Florence. The dedication page had been altered and the principal librarian to the Laurentian, Angelo Maria Bandini suggested that the author was Servandus, a follower of St. Benedict, and that it had been produced at Monte Cassino around the 540s. This claim was accepted for the next hundred years, establishing it as the oldest copy of the Vulgate, but scholars in Germany noted the similarity to 9th-century texts. In 1888, Giovanni Battista de Rossi established that the Codex was related to the Bibles mentioned by Bede. This also established that Amiatinus was related to the Greenleaf Bible fragment in the British Library. Although de Rossi's attribution removed 150 years from the age of the Codex, it remains the oldest version of the Vulgate and the oldest complete Christian bible in any language. As the primary source of the Vulgate, the manuscript was of particular importance to the Catholics during the Counter-Reformation. Protestant translations derived from the original language of the Scriptures, but the Latin text of the Amiatinus was earlier than any then-known Hebrew manuscript, making it a "major piece of propaganda in the battle for textual precedence". In 1587 Pope Sixtus V demanded the book be sent to Rome where it was consulted for a new papal edition of the Bible, the Sixtine Vulgate; although in the event, little or no use was made of its readings in either the Sistine or subsequent Sixto-Clementine official Vulgate editions, whose editors rather preferred later medieval Vulgate texts and editions now known to have been heavily corrupted by non-Vulgate readings. In view of the many accumulated corruptions in all published editions of the Vulgate so far, the Oxford University Press accepted in 1878 a proposal from classicist John Wordsworth (later Bishop of Salisbury) to produce a new critical edition of the Vulgate New Testament. This was eventually published as Nouum Testamentum Domini nostri Iesu Christi Latine, secundum editionem sancti Hieronymi in three volumes between 1889 and 1954; the Codex Amiatinus being a primary source for the entire text; which also followed this manuscript in presenting the text in sense lines, cola et commata without any other indication of punctuation. In 1907 Pope Pius X commissioned the Benedictine monks in Rome to prepare a critical edition of Jerome's Vulgate, entitled Biblia Sacra iuxta latinam vulgatam versionem, which eventually emerged as a counterpart Old Testament to the Oxford New Testament, following largely the same critical principles, and according similar primary status to the Codex Amiatinus text (other than for the Psalms); and similarly deriving its layout, cola et commata from Amiatinus.

á¶œá´¸ Hablar Fisno: One of the key traits of French is the loss of s, but this trait does exist in one other Romance language, albeit only in particular dialects. That is, in Spanish. The Castilian language, as spoken in Andalucia (southern Spain), the Canary Islands, and the former Spanish Caribbean (mainly Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic) has lost /s/ in most positions but usually finally, either becoming /h/ or entirely silent. Thus, just like French, in these dialects pluralization can only be indicated by the article and conjugation of verbs. Compare los hombres aman las mujeres /loh om.bre a.man lah mu.hÎµr.e/ (the men love the women) with el hombre ama la mujere /Îµl om.bre a.ma la mu.hÎµr/ (the man loves the woman). This has also created a situation of hypercorrection, where speakers of these dialects incorrectly insert /s/ into places where they shouldn't be due to not having a native understanding of where this phoneme should be in the standard dialect - thus words such as fino (fine) become fisno, leading to this practice being given the ironic name of hablar fisno - to attempt to talk in a fancy way, but incorrectly. These dialects also have some other very Francophone traits through pure coincidence, such as ch /tÊƒ/ being pronounced as /Êƒ/, nasalisation of vowels preceding /n/. and final /Îµr/ being articulated as simply /e/.

Australian Frontier Wars: Waterloo Creek Massacre (26 Jan 1838) Result: Colonial victory, Aboriginals driven from Gwydir River territory. Was a battle at Waterloo Creek between Kamilaroi Aboriginals and Sydney mounted police. Sydney mounted police (2 sergeants, 20 troopers) led by Major James Nunn pursued the Kamilaroi to upper Gwydir River, following the murder of 5 British stockmen in recently established pastoral runs on the upper Gwydir River area of New South Wales. On the morning of Jan 26, there was a surprise attack on Nunn's party, leaving Corporal Hannan wounded with a spear in his leg and 5 dead Aboriginals. The Aboriginals fled down river and the remaining British pursued them, led by Lieutenant George Cobban. Cobban's party found their quarry about a mile down the river at a point now known as Waterloo Creek, where a second engagement took place. The encounter lasted several hours and no Aboriginals were captured. Modern estimates put at 300 dead Aboriginals with no British casualties.

The probable number of surviving individual copies is much higher, estimated at around 125,000 in Germany alone. Through statistical analysis, it is estimated that the number of lost editions is at least 20,000. cleaned_message: Description of the Codex Amiatinus: The symbol for it is written am or A (Wordsworth). It is preserved in an immense tome, measuring 19+1â„4 inches (49 cm) high, 13+3â„8 inches (34 cm) in breadth, and 7 inches (18 cm) thick, and weighs over 75 pounds (34 kg) â€“ so impressive, as Hort says, as to fill the beholder with a feeling akin to awe. The Book of Psalms is provided in Jerome's third version, translated from the Hebrew, rather than in the pre-Jerome Roman Psalter then standard in English bibles, or in Jerome's second, Gallican version, that was to supplant his Hebraic Psalms in most Vulgate bibles from the 9th century onwards. By contrast with case in most of the rest of the Old Testament, the Amiatinus psalms text is commonly considered an Â¹inferior witness of Jerome's Versio juxta Hebraicum; the presence of the 'Columba' series of psalm headings, also found in the Cathach of St. Columba, demonstrates that an Irish psalter must have been its source; but the text differs in many places from the best Irish manuscripts. The New Testament is preceded by the Epistula Hieronymi ad Damasum, Prolegomena to the four Gospels. The Codex Amiatinus qualifies as an illuminated manuscript as it has some decoration including two full-page miniatures, but these show little sign of the usual insular style of Northumbrian art and are clearly copied from Late Antique originals. It contains 1,040 leaves of strong, smooth vellum, fresh-looking today despite their great antiquity, arranged in quires of four sheets, or quaternions. It is written in uncial characters, large, clear, regular, and beautiful, two columns to a page, and 43 or 44 lines to a column. A little space is often left between words, but the writing is in general continuous. The text is divided into sections, which in the Gospels correspond closely to the Ammonian Sections. There are no marks of punctuation, but the skilled reader was guided into the sense by stichometric, or verse-like, arrangement into cola and commata, which correspond roughly to the principal and dependent clauses of a sentence. From this manner of writing the script is believed to have been modeled upon the Codex Grandior of Cassiodorus, but it may go back, perhaps, even to St. Jerome. Â¹ "Inferior Psalms": An unsubstantiated opinion of modern Latin Vulgate scholars when comparing to later corrupted Medieval manuscripts.

Though nominally Christian (with many beliefs that are in stark contrast to most Christian sects), Jehovah's Witnesses don't call themselves it. Instead they call themselves witnesses to 'Jehovah'. Who or what is Jehovah? Jehovah is an English mispronunciation of a Latin transliteration by 15th century Italian Friar Pietro Colonna Galatino, of the 2nd century Greek attempted transliteration of the Tetragrammaton or name of God as it is presented in the Old Testament - ×™×”×•×” (YHWH). Most Hebrew manuscripts do not contain the vowels of the term as it was a sin to pronounce it, and older ones that do show it have inconsistences in pronunciation even in the same manuscript. But a common approximation became jehovah (pronounced yehow/va in Latin/Greek), which entered English through protestant Bibles. However the j in the term was read incorrectly as if it was English j /dÊ’/ instead of Latin /j/ like y in English. The term was used in various English protestant Bibles but was revived by the 19th century Bible Student Movement which preferred the American Standard version, and eventually named themselves after Isaiah 43:10 in this version - "Ye are my witnesses, saith Jehovah, and my servant whom I have chosen; that ye may know and believe me, and understand that I am he: before me there was no God formed, neither shall there be after me."
